	London: Timo Glock will test for Toyota in Spain on Thursday after being given the all-clear following his big crash in Sundays German Grand Prix, the Formula One team said on Tuesday.    
	The 26-year-old German, who will join the team in Jerez, spent Sunday night in hospital in Ludfor precautionary checks and returned home on Monday before further medical tests.    
	Those tests have confirmed Timo suffered no injuries or concussion, Toyota said in a statement. Therefore he has been given the all-clear to return to the cockpit on Thursday before he competes in the Hungarian Grand Prix.         
	Jamshedpur: Three out of four seeded players started off well, posting first round wins on the opening day of the eighth Jamshedpur edition of The Telegraph Schools Chess tournament at the eastern wing of the JRD Tata Sports Complex on Wednesday. The star of the day, however, was Mandeep Mukhi of Chakradharpur. The unseeded player put it across city-mate and third seed Pritesh Mehta in 17 moves.    
	In the second round, top seed Kumar Sanu of Delhi Public School (Dhanbad) won easily with black against unseeded Karan Vakhaira from Carmel Junior College (CJC), Jamshedpur.        
	Paris: France and Bayern Munich winger Franck Ribery called his recent ankle-ligament tear the worst injury of his career and said he doesnt know when hell be back on the pitch. Its no doubt the worst wound of my career, Ribery told a newspaper on Wednesday.    
	He said it was impossible to predict a return date, but that he hopes to be back to training in September. He said he will miss a France friendly in Sweden on August 20, as well as the first two qualifying matches for the 2010 World Cup. However, he said he should be back in time to play against Romania on October 11.         
	Beijing: A China Tour golf tournament in Chengdu, postponed after a devastating earthquake hit Sichuan on May 12, has been rescheduled for early September, organisers said on Tuesday.    
	The Luxehills Championship had been scheduled for early June but was called off after the 7.9 magnitude quake hit the area, killing at least 70,000.    
	China as a whole is encouraging people to return to the area and visit, C.B. Fong, general manager of Luxehills International Country Club, said in a China Tour statement. 
